
[1]peninsula

   PENIN'SULA, n. [L. pene, almost, and insula, an isle.]

   1. A portion of land, connected with a continent by a narrow neck or
   isthmus, but nearly surrounded with water. Thus Boston stands on a
   peninsula.

   2. A large extent of country joining the main land by a part narrower
   than the tract itself. Thus Spain and Portugal are said to be situated
   on a peninsula.
